@startuml seq_atari_fujibus_paths
title Atari FujiBus Channel/Transport Paths Compared

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam packageStyle rectangle
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

actor "Atari app\n(fdrive.xex etc.)" as AtariApp
participant "fujinet-nio-lib\nAtari FujiBus client\nSLIP + FujiBus packets" as AtariLib

box "POSIX emulator path" #EEF7FF
participant "AltirraSDL\nAtari SIO bus" as Altirra
participant "netsio.atdevice\nAltirra custom device" as AtDevice
participant "netsiohub\nTCP custom-device side\nUDP NetSIO side" as NetSioHub
participant "UdpChannel\nChannelKind::UdpSocket" as UdpChannel
participant "AtariNetSioFujiBusChannel\nNetSIO/SIO adapter Channel" as NetSioAdapter
end box

box "fujinet-nio core" #F4FFF1
participant "FujiBusTransport\nTransportKind::FujiBus" as FujiBusTransport
participant "IOService / RoutingManager" as IOSvc
participant "FujiDevice / DiskDevice /\nFileDevice / Clock / ..." as Devices
end box

box "ESP32 Atari hardware path" #FFF8E8
participant "Atari SIO connector\nphysical pins" as SioConnector
participant "ESP32 UartChannel\nSIO data pins" as SioUart
participant "AtariSioFujiBusChannel\nChannelKind::SioGpio" as SioChannel
participant "AtariSioFujiBusFramer\nSIO W/R/checksum adapter" as SioFramer
end box

box "Other FujiBus byte-pipe paths" #F8F0FF
participant "BBC / MS-DOS / Amiga /\nPython FujiBus client" as OtherClient
participant "RS-232 / TCP / PTY / USB CDC\nChannel byte pipe" as OtherChannel
end box

== Shared client-side packet shape ==

AtariApp -> AtariLib : FujiNet API call\n(e.g. get mount slot)
AtariLib -> AtariLib : Build FujiBus packet\nSLIP encode bytes

note right of AtariLib
The new Atari NIO path speaks the same
FujiBus protocol as BBC, MS-DOS, Amiga,
Python, POSIX PTY/TCP, and USB CDC clients.
It does not use the legacy SIO transport.
end note

== POSIX emulator: Atari FujiBus over NetSIO ==

AtariLib -> Altirra : FujiBus bytes over Atari SIO calls
Altirra -> AtDevice : custom device SIO events
AtDevice -> NetSioHub : TCP NetSIO custom-device protocol
NetSioHub -> UdpChannel : UDP NetSIO packets
UdpChannel -> NetSioAdapter : raw NetSIO bytes

NetSioAdapter -> NetSioAdapter : unwrap NetSIO/SIO command frames\nrecover FujiBus byte stream
NetSioAdapter -> FujiBusTransport : Channel::read()\nSLIP + FujiBus bytes

FujiBusTransport -> FujiBusTransport : Decode SLIP\nparse FujiBusPacket
FujiBusTransport -> IOSvc : IORequest
IOSvc -> Devices : route by device id + command
Devices --> IOSvc : IOResponse
IOSvc --> FujiBusTransport : response
FujiBusTransport -> NetSioAdapter : Channel::write()\nSLIP + FujiBus response bytes

NetSioAdapter -> NetSioAdapter : wrap response as SIO complete/data/checksum\ninside NetSIO packets
NetSioAdapter -> UdpChannel : UDP NetSIO packets
UdpChannel -> NetSioHub : UDP
NetSioHub -> AtDevice : TCP custom-device protocol
AtDevice -> Altirra : SIO response bytes
Altirra --> AtariLib : FujiBus response bytes
AtariLib --> AtariApp : decoded result

note over UdpChannel,NetSioAdapter
POSIX needs this Atari-specific adapter only because
Altirra exposes SIO through the existing NetSIO custom
device protocol. The core still sees ordinary Channel bytes.
end note

== ESP32 hardware: Atari FujiBus over SIO GPIO ==

AtariLib -> SioConnector : Atari OS SIO command\nW/R around FujiBus payload
SioConnector -> SioUart : SIO UART bytes\npinmap().sio.uart
SioUart -> SioChannel : raw SIO command/data/checksum bytes
SioChannel -> SioFramer : ingest SIO W payload
SioFramer -> SioChannel : recovered SLIP + FujiBus bytes
SioChannel -> FujiBusTransport : Channel::read()\nSLIP + FujiBus bytes
FujiBusTransport -> IOSvc : IORequest
IOSvc -> Devices : route by device id + command
Devices --> IOSvc : IOResponse
IOSvc --> FujiBusTransport : response
FujiBusTransport -> SioChannel : Channel::write()\nSLIP + FujiBus response bytes
SioChannel -> SioFramer : queue response for pending SIO R
SioFramer -> SioChannel : SIO C/data/checksum bytes
SioChannel -> SioUart : UART TX
SioUart --> SioConnector : SIO response bytes
SioConnector --> AtariLib : Atari SIO read result\nFujiBus response payload

note over SioConnector,SioFramer
Current ESP32 Atari NIO selection is:
FN_BUILD_ATARI_FUJIBUS_SIO
  TransportKind::FujiBus
  ChannelKind::SioGpio

The ESP32 factory maps SioGpio to
AtariSioFujiBusChannel. That channel owns
the UartChannel, configures SIO control pins,
and uses AtariSioFujiBusFramer to translate
Atari SIO W/R/checksum traffic into the raw
FujiBus byte stream consumed by FujiBusTransport.
end note

== BBC / MS-DOS comparison ==

OtherClient -> OtherChannel : FujiBus bytes over RS-232/TCP/PTY/USB CDC
OtherChannel -> FujiBusTransport : Channel::read()\nSLIP + FujiBus bytes
FujiBusTransport -> IOSvc : IORequest
IOSvc -> Devices : route by device id + command
Devices --> IOSvc : IOResponse
IOSvc --> FujiBusTransport : response
FujiBusTransport --> OtherChannel : Channel::write()\nSLIP + FujiBus response bytes
OtherChannel --> OtherClient : FujiBus response bytes

note over OtherClient,OtherChannel
BBC and MS-DOS do not need a NetSIO/SIO adapter
when they use RS-232/TCP/PTY-style channels. Their
channel is already a raw byte pipe carrying FujiBus.
end note

@enduml
